<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900824-0001</DOCNO><DOCID>900824-0001.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Drexel Executive,   Others Hold 7% Stake   In Fruit of the Loom</HL><DATE>08/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   X.FRY FTL</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s former mergerschief, Leon Black, is part of a group that bought 3,750,000shares of Class A stock in Fruit of the Loom Inc. from FarleyInc.   Mr. Black's role was disclosed in a Securities andExchange Commission filing by FL Management, an investmentadvisory firm headed by Mr. Black and three other formerDrexel employees, John Hannan, Arthur Bilger and Craig Cogut.The group's holding amounts to 7% of Fruit of the Loom'sstock.</LP><TEXT>   The Black group is investing money on behalf of severalFrench institutions, which put up the cash to buy the Fruitof the Loom stock, Mr. Hannan said in an interview. TheFrench institutions formally made their investment as LandFree Investment Ltd.   Farley previously entered into a put option agreement thatgives Land Free Investment the right to require Farley topurchase its Fruit of the Loom stock, under certainconditions, at an exercise price of $15.54 between July 12and July 15, 1991.   The filing said the purchases were made for investmentreasons, and Mr. Hannan said the group didn't have anypresent intention to increase its holdings. Mr. Black, whileat Drexel, was a regular adviser to Farley Inc.'s chairman,William Farley.   The filing also disclosed that Messrs. Bilger, Black andCogut have an indirect interest in 3,660,000 Class A Fruit ofthe Loom shares which were previously acquired throughpartnerships that are partners in Champlain Associates. Inaddition, Messrs. Black and Cogut have an indirect interestin 141,153 shares of Class A stock owned by WicklowInvestment Associates, in which Mr. Cogut is a generalpartner.   Mr. Black also directly owns 124,000 Class A shares andMr. Cogut owns 34,264 Class A shares.</TEXT></DOC>